04585nam a22006375i 9780748641383DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222009stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97807486413837 a10.1515/97807486413832doi  a(DE-B1597)615118  a(OCoLC)1306540985  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0270502bisacsh1 aDanchev, Alex, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOn Art and War and Terror /cAlex Danchev. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b17 B/W illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction: Out of the Marvellous, or, Scholarship and the Magic Arts -- t1 The Artist and the Terrorist, or, The Paintable and the Unpaintable: Gerhard Richter and the Baader-Meinhof Group -- t2 The Face, or, Senseless Kindness: War Photography and the Ethics of Responsibility -- t3 Provenance, or, Authenticity: The Guitar Player and the Arc of a Life -- t4 Broomstick Horrors, or, The Fog-Walker in the Wood: Keeping up Appearances in the Great War -- t5 The Strategy of Still Life, or, Art and Current Affairs: Georges Braque and the Occupation -- t6 All This Happened, or, The Real Waugh: Sword of Honour and the Literature of the Second World War -- t7 The Secret Life, or, The Soldier’s Tale: Diaries and Diary-Keeping in War -- t8 Like a Dog, or, Animal House on the Night Shift: Kafka and Abu Ghraib -- t9 It’s All Fucked Up, or, The Non-Fiction Horror Movie: The Cinema and the War on Terror -- t10 Waiting for the Barbarians, or, The Hospitality of War: Civilisation and Barbarism in the War on Terror -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book, a collection of Alex Danchev's essays on the theme of art, war and terror, offers a sustained demonstration of the way in which works of art can help us to explore the most difficult ethical and political issues of our time: war, terror, extermination, torture and abuse.It takes seriously the idea of the artist as moral witness to this realm, considering war photography, for example, as a form of humanitarian intervention. War poetry, war films and war diaries are also considered in a broad view of art, and of war. Kafka is drawn upon to address torture and abuse in the war on terror; Homer is utilised to analyse current talk of 'barbarisation'. The paintings of Gerhard Richter are used to investigate the terrorists of the Baader-Meinhof group, while the photographs of Don McCullin and the writings of Vassily Grossman and Primo Levi allow the author to propose an ethics of small acts of altruism.This book examines the nature of war over the last century, from the Great War to a particular focus on the current 'Global War on Terror'. It investigates what it means to be human in war, the cost it exacts and the ways of coping. Several of the essays therefore have a biographical focus.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 4aPolitics. 7aHISTORY / Military / Pictorial.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074863915140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978074864138340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748641383423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748641383/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK